The Temporal Dead Zone is a behavior in JavaScript that occurs when declaring a variable with
the let and const keywords, but not with var. In ECMAScript 6, accessing a let or const
variable before its declaration (within its scope) causes a ReferenceError. The time span when




that happens, between the creation of a variable’s binding and its declaration, is called the
temporal dead zone.
Let's see this behavior with an example,
function somemethod() { 
  console.log(counter1); // undefined 
  console.log(counter2); // ReferenceError 
  var counter1 = 1; 
  let counter2 = 2; 
}

